3.28 .328(Proposal to Remove Template Template Parameters)J
41 152 :M
.506(Introduction)A
41 176 :M
f0_10 sf
-.053(Template parameters can currently be one of four kinds:)A
54 200 :M
<A5>S
62 200 :M
-.109(Types)A
54 212 :M
<A5>S
62 212 :M
-.028(Integral or enumeration values; arguments are constant integral expressions)A
54 224 :M
<A5>S
62 224 :M
-.087(Pointers or references; arguments are external-linkage names or their addresses)A
54 236 :M
<A5>S
62 236 :M
-.021(Templates, i.e. \322template template parameters\323)A
41 260 :M
.051 .005(Most current implementations handle the first three kinds, but not the last.  To my knowledge there are no commercial)J
41 272 :M
-.026(implementations which handle template template parameters.)A
41 296 :M
-.035(When some members of core-III met informally between meetings to discuss core-III issues \(see N1080\), there was)A
41 308 :M
.027 .003(considerable support for removing template template parameters from the language.  \(This position was not unanimous;)J
41 320 :M
.061 .006(in particular, John Wilkinson said that SGI wants to keep template template parameters in the language.\))J
41 356 :M
f1_10 sf
5.382 .538(Incomplete Specification)J
41 380 :M
f0_10 sf
.011 .001(The specification of template template parameters is currently incomplete in the working paper.  In particular, there is no)J
41 392 :M
-.013(description of how argument deduction is to be done.  Prior to partial specialization, it was assumed that deduction of)A
41 404 :M
.041 .004(template template arguments, and types used in them, was simple and unique.  For example:)J
76 427 :M
f3_8 sf
-.773(template<template X<class T> > struct A { X<int*> y; };)A
76 438 :M
-.784(template<class T> struct B { };)A
76 449 :M
-.772(A<B> ab;  // X is deduced to be B, so ab.y is type B<int*>)A
41 472 :M
f0_10 sf
-.007(But how does partial specialization fit?  For example:)A
76 495 :M
f3_8 sf
-.773(template<template X<class T> > struct A { X<int*> y; };)A
76 506 :M
-.778(template<class T> struct B { };      //1)A
76 517 :M
-.778(template<class T> struct B<T*> { };  //2)A
76 528 :M
-.768(A<B> ab;  // what is X deduced to be?  Is X<int*> instantiated from  //1 or //2 ?)A
41 552 :M
f0_10 sf
.031 .003(There may be a simple solution here, such as considering the primary class template and its partial specializations to be)J
41 564 :M
.091 .009(a family, so that X is deduced to be the template family B.  Or similarly, that the partial specializations are really just)J
41 576 :M
-.016(additional attributes of the primary template, so X is deduced to be the primary B yet )A
382 576 :M
f3_8 sf
-.91(X<int*)A
412 576 :M
f0_10 sf
.203 .02(> instantiates the partial)J
41 588 :M
-.025(specialization of B.)A
41 612 :M
-.024(There are probably additional issues like this one which need to be resolved if template template parameters are to stay in)A
41 624 :M
.22 .022(the language.  Yet there has been very little interest in investigating such issues, which implies that very little thought)J
41 636 :M
-.009(has been given to template template parameters.)A
41 660 :M
.251 .025(It is somewhat late to begin such an investigation now.)J
